      "text": "The talk is long and dense but presented well with an occasional bit of humor. The following presentation and panel discussion are also excellent. I will pull a few key points from the speaker's notes. [https://doctorow.medium.com/my-mcluhan-lecture-on-enshittification-ea343342b9bc post]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "dafad941fc2f0387",
      "text": "It’s a three stage process: First, platforms are good to their users; then they abuse their users to make things better for their business customers; finally, they abuse those business customers to claw back all the value for themselves. Then, they die."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f14fdc3b032b627b",
      "text": "There are four forces that discipline companies, serving as constraints on their enshittificatory impulses:"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "aa3fb3848ef0c324",
      "text": "First: Competition. Companies that fear you will take your business elsewhere are cautious about worsening quality or raising prices."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3873a8bd3872d627",
      "text": "Second: Regulation. Companies that fear a regulator will fine them more than they expect to make from cheating, will cheat less."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bc5e2e03f355222d",
      "text": "Third: Self-help. Computers are extremely flexible, and so are the digital products and services we make from them. That means that users can always avail themselves of programs that undo the anti-features that shift value from them to a company’s shareholders."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cc738984590b857f",
      "text": "Fourth and finally: Workers. Tech workers have very low union density, but that doesn’t mean that tech workers don’t have labor power. The historical “talent shortage” of the tech sector meant that workers enjoyed a lot of leverage over their bosses. Workers who disagreed with their bosses could quit and walk across the street and get another job — a better job."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "299ca13ff84d957e",
      "text": "There are four constraints that prevent enshittification: competition, regulation, self-help and labor. To reverse enshittification and guard against its reemergence, we must restore and strengthen each of these."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f2eee59f9a06c51c",
      "text": "We’re seeing bold, muscular, global action on competition, regulation and labor, with self-help bringing up the rear. It’s not a moment too soon, because the bad news is, enshittification is coming to every industry.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "6283fc9e3c03165d",
      "text": "The internet isn’t more important than the climate emergency, nor gender justice, racial justice, genocide, or inequality. But the internet is the terrain we’ll fight those fights on. Without a free, fair and open internet, the fight is lost before it’s joined."
    }
